eshHeading><DescriptorName UI="D049674" MajorTopicYN="N">History, 21st Century</DescriptorName></MeshHeading><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI="D006801" MajorTopicYN="N">Humans</DescriptorName></MeshHeading><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI="D012586" MajorTopicYN="N">Science</DescriptorName><QualifierName UI="Q000266" MajorTopicYN="Y">history</QualifierName></MeshHeading></MeshHeadingList><PersonalNameSubjectList><PersonalNameSubject><LastName>Sipponen</LastName><ForeName>Mika</ForeName><Initials>M</Initials></PersonalNameSubject></PersonalNameSubjectList></MedlineCitation><PubmedData><History><PubMedPubDate PubStatus="pubmed"><Year>2021</Year><Month>8</Month><Day>7</Day><Hour>6</Hour><Minute>0</Minute></PubMedPubDate><PubMedPubDate PubStatus="medline"><Year>2021</Year><Month>11</Month><Day>4</Day><Hour>6</Hour><Minute>0</Minute></PubMedPubDate><PubMedPubDate PubStatus="entrez"><Year>2021</Year><Month>8</Month><Day>6</Day><Hour>12</Hour><Minute>35</Minute></PubMedPubDate></History><PublicationStatus>ppublish</PublicationStatus><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">34357669</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="doi">10.1002/anie.202109992</ArticleId></ArticleIdList><ReferenceList><Reference><Citation>The work started as a side project of Postdoctoral Fellow Adrian Moreno in the Sustainable Materials Chemistry (SUSMATCHEM) research group. The original idea was to esterify lignin with unsaturated fatty acids to achieve nanoparticles that could be cross-linked using free radical chemistry. Despite initial success, Dr. Moreno was curious to test pH stability of lignin oleate nanoparticles without the cross-linking to maintain their biodegradability. The results were unexpected and encouraged us to tailor properties and elucidate structure-function relationship of these nanoparticles. Collaboration within the department enriched the work and allowed us to harness these surface-functionalized particles in advanced sustainable materials.</Citation></Reference></ReferenceList></Pubm